ce:section.ce:para:
Levofloxacin, a representative of quinolone antibiotic with slightly positive charge (+1.32 mV, Fig. 1
                     C), exhibits the broad-spectrum antibacterial effect through DNA - binding proteins combination or efflux pump mechanism [36]. Nevertheless, it is documented that levofloxacin suffers from drug resistance (after two weeks or below) and poor solubility in the physiological environment, thus posing certain barriers to its clinical application. In this work, levofloxacin-based carbon dots (LCDs) with low drug resistance and good solubility were synthesized, which retained the broad-spectrum antibacterial bioactivities of levofloxacin (Scheme 1
                     ). The water solubility, stability and biosafety of LCDs were outstanding. Meanwhile, LCDs with the positive charge were prone to attaching to negatively-charged bacteria via electrostatic interaction, exhibiting broad-spectrum antibacterial activity and reducing the risk of development of resistance. In detail, the minimum bactericidal concentration (MIC) of LCDs was 0.125 μg/mL and lower than levofloxacin hydrochloride against Staphylococcus aureus (S. aureus) and Escherichia coli (E. coli) within 38 passages. In addition, the experiments in vivo showed that the LCDs had excellent antibacterial activity and improved curative effect in animal infected models involving the bacterial infection wound model and pneumonia model. The most significant findings of this work were drug-based synthetic designment and synergistic antibacterial mechanism, including the reservation the antibacterial groups and the process of killing bacteria of LCDs without other extra stimulation ascribing to cationic properties and ROS-induced oxidative stress.
